HEADWORD: Mine
<hw>Mine</hw> <pr>(m⟦emac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety>
<def>See <er>Mien</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mine
<hw>Mine</hw> <pr>(m⟦imac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>pron. & a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>min</ets>, fr. AS. <ets>m⟦imac⟧n</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mijn</ets>,
OS., OFries., & OHG. <ets>m⟦imac⟧n</ets>, G. <ets>mein</ets>, Sw. & Dan.
<ets>min</ets>, Icel. <ets>minn</ets>, Goth. <ets>meins</ets> my, mine,
<ets>meina</ets> of me, and E. <ets>me</ets>. ⟦root⟧187. See
<er>Me</er>, and cf. <er>My</er>.]</ety> <def>Belonging to me; my. Used
as a pronominal to me; my. Used as a pronominal adjective in the
predicate; <as>as, ⟦ldquo⟧Vengeance is <ex>mine</ex>; I will
repay.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Rom. xii. 19</au></as>. Also, in the old style, used
attributively, instead of <xex>my</xex>, before a noun beginning with a
vowel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I kept myself from <qex>mine</qex> iniquity.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
xviii. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Mine</xex> is often used absolutely, the thing
possessed being understood; as, his son is in the army, <xex>mine</xex>
in the navy.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When a man deceives me once, says the Italian proverb, it is his
fault; when twice, it is <qex>mine</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Horne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This title honors me and <qex>mine</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She shall have me and <qex>mine</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mine
<hw>Mine</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>miner</ets>, L.
<ets>minare</ets> to drive animals, in LL. also, to lead, conduct, dig a
mine (cf. E. <ets>lode</ets>, and <ets>lead</ets> to conduct), akin to
L. <ets>minari</ets> to threaten; cf. Sp. <ets>mina</ets> mine, conduit,
subterraneous canal, a spring or source of water, It. <ets>mina</ets>.
See <er>Menace</er>, and cf. <er>Mien</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To dig a mine or pit in the earth; to get ore,
metals, coal, or precious stones, out of the earth; to dig in the earth
for minerals; to dig a passage or cavity under anything in order to
overthrow it by explosives or otherwise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form subterraneous tunnel or hole; to form a
burrow or lodge in the earth; <as>as, the <ex>mining</ex>
cony</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mine
<hw>Mine</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mined</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mining</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To dig away, or otherwise remove, the substratum or
foundation of; to lay a mine under; to sap; to undermine; hence, to ruin
or destroy by slow degrees or secret means.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>mined</qex> the walls.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Too lazy to cut down these immense trees, the spoilers . . . had
<qex>mined</qex> them, and placed a quantity of gunpowder in the
cavity.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dig into, for ore or metal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lead veins have been traced . . . but they have not been
<qex>mined</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ure.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To get, as metals, out of the earth by
digging.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The principal ore <qex>mined</qex> there is the bituminous
cinnabar.</q> <rj><qau>Ure.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mine
<hw>Mine</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. LL. <ets>mina</ets>. See
<er>Mine</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A subterranean cavity or passage</def>;
<specif>especially:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A pit or excavation in
the earth, from which metallic ores, precious stones, coal, or other
mineral substances are taken by digging; -- distinguished from the pits
from which stones for architectural purposes are taken, and which are
called <xex>quarries</xex>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A
cavity or tunnel made under a fortification or other work, for the
purpose of blowing up the superstructure with some explosive
agent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 926 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any place where ore, metals, or precious stones are
got by digging or washing the soil; <as>as, a placer
<ex>mine</ex></as>.</def><-- esp. in <cref>gold mine</cref> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <mark>(Fig.)</mark>: <def>A rich source of wealth or
other good.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>An explosive device placed
concealed in a location, on land or at sea, where an enemy vehicle or
enemy personnel may pass through, having a triggering mechanism which
detects people or vehicles, and which will explode and kill or maim
personnel or destroy or damage vehicles. A mine placed at sea (formerly
called a <altname>torpedo</altname>, see <er>torpedo</er>{2}
<sd>(a)</sd>) is also called an <ecol><b>marine mine</b></ecol> and
<ecol><b>underwater mine</b></ecol> and sometimes called a
<styp><ecol><b>floating mine</b></ecol></styp>, even though it may be
anchored to the floor of the sea and not actually float freely. A mine
placed on land (formerly called a <altname>torpedo</altname>, see
<er>torpedo</er>{3}), usually buried, is called a <ecol><b>land
mine</b></ecol>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mine dial</b></col>, <cd>a form of magnetic compass used
by miners.</cd> -- <col><b>Mine pig</b></col>, <cd>pig iron made wholly
from ore; in distinction from <contr>cinder pig</contr>, which is made
from ore mixed with forge or mill cinder.</cd> -- <col><b>gold
mine</b></col> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>a mine where gold is obtained.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <mark>(Fig.)</mark> <cd>a rich source of wealth or other
good; same as <er>Mine</er> 3.</cd></cs> <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mined</ent>⟦br⟧
